    <refsection id="Description_CEAS_ZDiode">
        <title>Description</title>
        <para>
            This block is a zener diode with 3 working areas. The first area is when Vd (diode voltage) is greater than Maxexp*Vt. The output current is :
        </para>
        <para>
            <latex>
                \begin{eqnarray}
                Iout = Ids*(\exp(Maxexp) * (1+\frac{\Large{Vd}}{\Large{Vt}}-Maxexp)-1) + \frac{\Large{Vd}}{\Large{R}}
                \end{eqnarray}
            </latex>
        </para>
        <para>
            The second one is when Vd + Bv is lower than -Maxexp*Nbv*Vt, so output current is given by:
        </para>
        <para>
            <latex>
                \begin{eqnarray}
                Iout = -Ids-Ibv* \exp(Maxexp) * (1- \frac{\Large{Vd+Bv}}{\Large{Nbv*Vt}} - Maxexp) + \frac{\Large{Vd}}{\Large{R}}
                \end{eqnarray}
            </latex>
        </para>
        <para>
            In the other cases, Iout is given by this formula:
        </para>
        <para>
            <latex>
                \begin{eqnarray}
                Iout = -Ids * (\exp(Vd/Vt)-1) - Ibv * \exp(\frac{\Large{-Vd+Bv}}{\Large{Nbv*Vt}}) + \frac{\Large{Vd}}{\Large{R}}
                \end{eqnarray}
            </latex>
        </para>
        <para>
            If Bv is exceeded, this zener diode (unlike the simple diode) permits current in reverse direction.
        </para>
    </refsection>
